Introduction¶

This notebook contains an analysis of a dataset containing information on medical appointments in Brazil. The focus of the analysis is on predicting whether or not patients will show up for their scheduled appointments.

This analysis is carried out as part of the project requirements for the Udacity Data Analyst Nanodegree programme which requires demonstrating the ability to conduct independent data analysis and to communicate observed findings.

The analysis aims to answer the following questions:

  • What factors are important for predicting whether or not a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?
  • Are there any trends or patterns in the data that can help us understand why some patients miss their appointments?
  • Given the statistical relationship between receiving SMS messages and attending appointments, if a more efficient bulk text system is introduced, would this significantly improve attendance of scheduled appointments?

From the above, the observed initial cleaning that needs to happen are the following

  • Correct the PatientId and AppointmentID columns to int64
  • Replace Patients with Age = -1 by the median age of the patients having the same Gender and in the same Neighbourhood

as the patient. The median was chosen rather than the mean to prevent using an average that is skewed by extreme values and is not representative of the associated demographic.

  • Patients with Handcap value greater than 0 will be replaced with 1 since any number greater than 0 means that they have some kind of handicap condition and is therefore not a healthy subject.
  • There are no missing values so there is no need to remove rows with NaN values (missing values) from the dataset.

Data Cleaning¶

In [ ]:
# Correct the IDs to int64
initial_df["PatientId"] = initial_df["PatientId"].astype(np.int64)
initial_df["AppointmentID"] = initial_df["AppointmentID"].astype(np.int64)
In [ ]:
# Replace Patients with Age = -1 by the median age of the patients having the same Gender and in the same Neighbourhood as the patient

median_age_neighbourhood = initial_df.groupby(["Gender", "Neighbourhood"], as_index=False)["Age"].median()

initial_df[["Age", "Gender", "Neighbourhood"]] = initial_df[["Age", "Gender", "Neighbourhood"]].apply(lambda x: (median_age_neighbourhood[(median_age_neighbourhood["Gender"] == x["Gender"]) & (median_age_neighbourhood["Neighbourhood"] == x[2])]["Age"].tolist()[-1], x["Gender"], x["Neighbourhood"]) if x["Age"] == -1 else x, axis=1)

initial_df["Age"] = initial_df["Age"].astype(np.int64)
In [ ]:
# Replace Patients with Handcap value greater than 0 with 1
initial_df["Handcap"] = np.where(initial_df["Handcap"] == 0, 0, 1)
initial_df["Handcap"] = initial_df["Handcap"].astype(np.int64)

From the above data visual, we can conclude that the single most important factor that impacts whether patient will show up for their appointment or not is the number of days between when patients schedule their appointment and the actual appointment date. More details will be looked into in the subsequent research questions

It is also interesting to see that the age of the patient is also a significant predictor in whether the patient will show up or not for their appointment or not.

"AppointmentID" showing up as significant implies that while it may not be obvious, recent changes in hospital operations (since more recent Appointment IDs will have larger integer numbers) are impacting whether the patient will show up for their appointment or not. This could be instrumental in providing a recommendation for a path to resolving the patient no-show issues.

Finally, whether the patient has a Scholarship or not is a predictor to whether they will show up for their appointment or not.

In summary, the five top significant predictive factors to whether or not a patient will show up for their appointment are as follows:

  • Days_Scheduled_Appointment (61.53%)
  • Age (6.16%)
  • AppointmentID (4.46%)
  • SMS_received (4.03%)
  • Scholarship (3.86%)

There are a number of other visuals produced. This can be seen in the no_show_analyses.ipynb notebook. However, for the sake of conciseness and relevance for this report, the above visuals have been presented.

From the data visuals presented, the following trends and patterns could be observed to be a possible pointer to why some patients miss their appointments are as follows:

  • It appears that if the difference in days between the scheduled day and the appointment day is greater than 0 (meaning the appointment is on a different day from the schedule day), there is a higher probability that the patient will miss the appointment.

  • The above observation can be seen for the difference in weeks between the scheduled day and the appointment day. Those appointments with weeks difference greater than 0 had a higher probabiility that the patient will miss the appointment

  • It was interesting to observe that persons who received SMS had a higher probability to miss their appointment that those that did not receive SMS's. This is a curious situation especially as it would be reasonable to assume that persons who got SMS's would have less chances of missing their appointments. This could be tied with the general hospital operations and could be a point of resolving the No-shows issues

  • It was also observed that if the patient was a Baby, a member of the older population or an adult, they were more likely to attend their appointment. However, if the patient was a Child, or an Adolescent, they were more likely to miss their appointment.

  • Finally, if the patient was from the neighbourhood of "Jardim Camburi", there was a higher probability that they would not miss their appointment. If they were from other neighbourhoods there was an increased likelihood that they would miss their patient's appointment.

  • With all of these observations, if a patient fixes an appointment say 1 week from the appointment date; had received SMS from the hospital, is an adolescent and does not live in the neighbourhood of "Jardim Camburi", it is almost certain that they would be miss their appointment.

Research Question 3:¶

Given the statistical relationship between receiving SMS messages and attending appointments, if a more efficient bulk text system is introduced, would this significantly improve attendance of scheduled appointments?¶

Given the research question above, improving the SMS messaging platform will only improve the attendance of scheduled appointment if it can be established that there is a statistically significant relationship between the SMS_received and No-shows.

To answer this question on statistical significance of the variables, I will be working with the hypothesis below:

  1. $H_0$: There is no statistical relationship between the SMS_recieved and the No-shows variable
  2. $H_1$: There is a statistical relationship between the SMS_recieved and the No-shows variable

I will be using the Chi-square test to check the above hypothesis, using a significance level ($\alpha$) of $0.05$. Therefore, if the p-value of the test is less than or equal to the significance level, it means that $H_0$ will be rejected and if the p-value is greater than the significance level, then $H_0$ will not be rejected.

$H_0$ being rejected implies that improving the SMS messaging platform will contribute to improving the attendance of scheduled appointment.

In [ ]:
# perform the chi-square test in the function below
perform_chi_square_test(initial_df, "SMS_received", "No-show-codes")
No-show-codes 0 1 All
SMS_received
0 62510 12535 75045
1 25698 9784 35482
All 88208 22319 110527 
p value is 0.0


There is a statistically significant relationship between the two variables (reject H0)

From the above result, the p-value is less than $\alpha$, therefore improving the SMS messaging platform will contribute to improving the attendance of scheduled appointment.

However, it is important to state that as gleaned from some of previous analysis, simply increasing the reach of the SMS, does not guarantee that the number of no-shows will reduce. If anything, it appears that people who receive the SMS have a higher tendency to miss their appointment.

Consequently, there might be a need to look into, perhaps the contents of the SMS being sent, the timing of the sent SMS and the corresponding frequency of the messages sent. Therefore, a holistic improvement of the SMS platform together with some other measures to remind people who have booked their appointment longer into the future could positively impact the attendance rates.

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, this analyses has been performed on a dataset containing information on medical appointments in Brazil. The focus of the analysis is on understanding factors that predict whether or not patients will show up for their scheduled appointments. The observed findings are as follows:

  • The five top significant predictive factors to whether or not a patient will show up for their appointment are as follows:

    • Days_Scheduled_Appointment (61.53%)
    • Age (6.16%)
    • AppointmentID (4.46%)
    • SMS_received (4.03%)
    • Scholarship (3.86%)

  • If the difference in days between the scheduled day and the appointment day is greater than 0, there is a higher probability that the patient will miss the appointment.

  • Appointments with weeks difference greater than 0 had a higher probabiility that the patient will miss the appointment.

  • Persons who received SMS had a higher probability to miss their appointment that those that did not receive SMS's.

  • If the patient was a Baby, a member of the older population or an adult, they were more likely to attend their appointment. However, if the patient was a Child, or an Adolescent, they were more likely to miss their appointment.

  • If the patient was from the neighbourhood of "Jardim Camburi", there was a higher probability that they would not miss their appointment. If they were from other neighbourhoods there was an increased likelihood that they would miss their patient's appointment.

  • From the statistical analyis conducted, the p-value was less than $\alpha$, which implies that improving the SMS messaging platform will contribute to improving the attendance of scheduled appointment.

However, simply increasing the reach of the SMS, does not guarantee that the number of no-shows will reduce. Consequently, there might be value in looking into the contents of the SMS being sent, the timing of the sent SMS and the corresponding frequency of the messages sent. Therefore, a holistic improvement of the SMS platform together with some other measures to remind people who have booked their appointment longer into the future could positively impact the attendance rates.

Limitations of the analysis¶

  • This analysis was carried out to observe patterns that exist within the provided dataset. No causality analysis was carried out and the patterns observed may be symptoms of other variables not captured by the data.
  • The results of this analysis are not necessarily representative of the population of patients' appointment in Brazil, as there is no information as to the accuracy and relevance of the data collected to the Brazillian population in the first place.
